postcontent:
I have for sale a Smith and Wesson Model 1, Second Issue .22 Pistol.  This pistol fires the old .22 black powder cartridges.  I have a letter of authenticity from smith and wesson for this gun, and according to the letter and the gun condition it looks to be all original.  

The guns where popular amongst the civil war soldiers and travelers heading west.  The specific gun was sold by smith and wesson to J. W. Storrs, in New York, NY on September 11, 1866.  J. W. Storrs was the sole agent for smith and wesson from 1857 to 1869.

The letter verifies the guns was originally manufactured with a 3 3/16 inch Blue barrel, blue cylinder, and a silver plated brass frame, with smooth rosewood grips.  It also has the initials "J. W. Blood" engraved in two different spots on it.  Smith and wesson indicated it was common for owners to have there new guns engraved at the store where they where bought as they typically had an on staff jeweler.

Price is $500.00

Medical bills force sale.
